{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1084.erdos_1084.variants.upper_d1 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1084.erdos_1084.variants.upper_d1.","id":"vf_2928ccfe2e8d7733","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1084: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $f_d(n)$ be minimal such that in any collection of $n$ points in $\\mathbb{R}^d$, all of distance at least $1$ apart, there are at most $f_d(n)$ many pairs of points which are distance $1$ apart. Estimate $f_d(n)$. Current best: Erd\\H{o}s \\cite{Er46b} showed\\[f_2(n)<3n-cn^{1/2}\\]for some constant $c>0$, which the triangular lattice shows is the best possible up to the value of $c$. In \\cite{Er75f} he speculated that the triangular lattice is exactly the best possible, and in particular\\[f_2(3n^2+3n+1)=9n^2+6n.\\]In \\cite{Er75f} he claims the existence of $c_1,c_2>0$ such that\\[6n-c_1n^{2/3}< f_3(n) < 6n-c_2n^{2/3}.\\]See [223] for the analogous problem with maximal distance $1$. Prize: no. OEIS: A045945. Tags: distances, geometry.","id":"vf_49ee69ee327bfda0","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1084.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_2928ccfe2e8d7733","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:1084","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_2928ccfe2e8d7733","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"vf_49ee69ee327bfda0","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted find